h, the rest of the config directory including the keystore remains available from the image. I'm setting up an init container that copies the existing keystore from the image, then uses the elasticsearch-keystore command to add the S3 credentials (access key and secret key) from environment variables sourced from a Kubernetes secret, writing everything to a shared volume. I'm reconsidering the approach since I'm not certain about the elasticsearch-keystore flags. Instead, I'll have the init container work directly in the standard Elasticsearch config directory and then copy the keystore to the shared volume.\n\nWriting init container script... I'm second-guessing whether `path_style_access` is actually a valid client-level setting in Elasticsearch 8.11 — it might be a repository-level configuration instead. Let me verify against the official docs to make sure I'm using the correct settings for the S3 client configuration. I need to verify that a restart is actually necessary since the task specifies only restarting if needed. I'm updating the elasticsearch.yml configuration and adding a new init container with a volume mount, both of which require a pod restart. The cluster is currently green with 5 nodes total, so a rolling restart of the elasticsearch statefulset should be safe with the es-data-new nodes still available. Now I'm writing out the complete Kubernetes resources starting with the MinIO service.\n\nFinishing the service definition...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation approach. I could use `kubectl patch` with a strategic merge patch to modify the StatefulSet, but that gets complex with the init container and volume configuration. It might be cleaner to fetch the current StatefulSet definition, make the necessary changes locally, and reapply it. I also need to update the ConfigMap with the MinIO endpoint settings and verify what port MinIO is actually using inside the cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_d