mount issue entirely since I'm not trying to persist the keystore changes through a volume—I'm just configuring it once the container is running and then reloading the settings.\n\nThe durability problem still exists though. If a pod restarts, those credentials disappear. I could set up a cronjob to periodically re-add them, but that's clunky. A better approach is to have the init container pre-populate the keystore into a temporary location, then use a wrapper script in the main container to copy it into place during startup before Elasticsearch fully initializes. The postStart hook timing is risky since Elasticsearch reads the keystore during startup, so there could be a race condition. I'm reconsidering the environment variable approach, but the constraints rule that out. Instead, I'm thinking about wrapping the container's entrypoint with a custom script that copies the keystore from the init container's shared volume before Elasticsearch actually starts, then executes the normal startup command.\n\nWriting entrypoint wrapper... I'm reconsidering the approach—maybe a `postStart` lifecycle hook would be cleaner, where it adds the S3 credentials to the keystore after ES initializes but before it fully starts up. Though I need to verify the timing of when postStart runs relative to ES reading the keystore configuration.\n\nActually, the real issue is that ES reads the keystore early during startup, so even if postStart adds credentials later, I'd need to call `reload_secure_settings` to make ES pick them up. For a clean initial setup, the credentials need to be in the keystore before ES starts reading it.\n\nLooking at the actual error trace, it's the main container itself that's failing when trying to run `elasticsearch-keystore add` internally as part of its startup sequence. The problem is the keystore file is read-only or there's a permissions issue preventing the keystore modification from succeeding.\n\nThe real solution is to avoid mounting the keystore as a