{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CHLnjPckrP22GikPhVojow","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The old subPath mount is STILL there despite my patch! The `kubectl apply` is not removing the old volumeMount. This is a strategic merge patch behavior issue - when you have a volumeMount with a different `name`+`subPath` combination, strategic merge patches don't remove old mounts; they merge by `mountPath`.\n\nActually no - the merge key for volumeMounts is `mountPath`, not `name`. So when I provided a volumeMount with `name: keystore-vol, mountPath: /keystore-source`, it was ADDED (new mountPath). \n\nThe old mount with `mountPath: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.keystore` wasn't removed because it has a different `mountPath`. When I applied the patched JSON, the old mount persisted because I didn't explicitly remove it - I only filtered out the old keystore-vol mounts and added back the new one, but `kubectl apply` should have replaced the entire volumeMounts list.\n\nActually, the issue is that `kubectl apply` uses strategic merge patch by default, which merges volumeMounts based on the `mountPath` as the merge key. So existing mounts with different paths are kept unless I explicitly delete them. To replace the entire list, I'd need to use `--force-conflicts` with server-side apply or use `kubectl replace`, though `kubectl replace --force` would delete and recreate the StatefulSet causing a full restart.\n\nI could instead use a JSON Patch with explicit `op: remove` and `op: add` operations to target the specific volumeMounts path.\n\nBut wait—I'm realizing the real problem isn't the `cp` command at all. The keystore file is already available at both `/keystore-source/elasticsearch.keystore` and `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.keystore` through the subPath mount, so they're the same file. The init container created it with S3 credentials. The actual issue is that Elasticsearch tries to write to the keystore during startup when processing the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` env var, and this write fails because the file is a bind mount. If I remove the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` env var, Elasticsearch won't attempt to write to the keystore—and since the cluster is already initialized, the passwords are stored in the security index anyway, so the bootstrap password in the keystore isn't needed after the first startup. The readiness probe authenticates using the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` env var, so I can't remove it without breaking health checks. A better approach would be to keep the env var for the probe but drop the keystore mount entirely—that way ES won't try to write S3 credentials to a mounted keystore on startup, and I can add them through the API after the pod is running.\n\nMy plan is to remove all the keystore-related mounts and the init container, do a rolling restart of the three pods to pick up the S3 settings in elasticsearch.yml, then manually add the S3 credentials to each pod's keystore and reload the secure settings.\n\nAfter that, I'll register the repository and create the snapshot. I'm aware this is a temporary fix—if pods restart later, the credentials would be lost—but for getting this one snapshot working, it's sufficient. A better long-term solution would use a postStart lifecycle hook that injects credentials into the keystore without needing to mount files.\n\nThe postStart hook approach is actually cleaner: it runs after the container starts, adds the S3 credentials to the keystore from environment variables, then reloads the secure settings. Since S3 credentials are only needed for snapshots (not during Elasticsearch startup), the timing works out fine.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a constraint issue here—using `secretKeyRef` in environment variables technically still exposes the credentials as env vars inside the container, which violates the requirement not to place credentials in env vars. I need to find a way to pass the secret values to the postStart hook without making them available as environment variables.\n\nInstead, I can mount the secret as a volume at a specific path and then read from those files directly in the lifecycle hook. This keeps the credentials out of env vars entirely—they're only accessible as files on the filesystem that the hook can read and pipe into the keystore command.\n\nThe timing concern with postStart is real though: if the hook tries to reload secure settings before Elasticsearch is actually listening, it'll fail. I could either skip the reload in postStart and do it manually after the pods restart, or have the hook retry the reload command until it succeeds.\n\nActually, there's a simpler path that avoids postStart hooks entirely. Since I'm restarting the pods anyway for the elasticsearch.yml changes, I can just add the credentials to the keystore in a running pod, let them persist, and then trigger the rolling restart. The keystore changes will survive the restart.\n\nSo the flow is: mount the secret volume with the S3 credentials, do a rolling restart, then exec into each pod to add those credentials to the keystore using the elasticsearch-keystore command, call the reload_secure_settings API, and finally register the repository and create the snapshot. For future pod restarts, I'd need a postStart hook to automatically re-add the credentials.\n\nActually, let me add that postStart hook now to make it self-healing—the credentials come from the mounted secret volume, so I'm not violating the constraint. The hook would add the credentials and reload them, with a retry loop to handle cases where Elasticsearch isn't ready immediately after startup. Now I need to implement the changes cleanly. I'll remove the keystore volume and init container entirely, add a volume mount for the secret, and set up a postStart hook to load the credentials. Since I'm changing the volume setup, I should also reconsider whether I still need the command override in the main container or if I can rely on the default image entrypoint.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":430,"cache_read_input_tokens":69087,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":430},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"823df5a8-cb94-4994-9da9-a4bc1dae2c2d","uuid":"5de057bd-452d-4e8f-a3f7-81d5766d9139","request_id":"req_011Ccf4gdevuoTSmrsiHBkh9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CHLnjPckrP22GikPhVojow","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The subPath mount keeps coming back via strategic merge. The real issue is that Elasticsearch's entrypoint writes to the keystore on startup (for `ELASTIC_PASSWORD`), which fails with any bind mount. I'll take a clean approach: mount the `es-secure-settings` secret as a volume and use a `postStart` lifecycle hook to populate the keystore from it (no env vars for credentials):"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":430,"cache_read_input_tokens":69087,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":430},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"823df5a8-cb94-4994-9da9-a4bc1dae2c2d","uuid":"f668b6c3-2c5d-40ef-b49a-e026525b5dc0","request_id":"req_011Ccf4gdevuoTSmrsiHBkh9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CHLnjPckrP22GikPhVojow","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KD4iPemdK12PU15Cx3hExw","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl get statefulset elasticsearch -n elasticsearch -o json > /tmp/es-sts3.json && python3 - <<'PYEOF'\nimport json\n\nwith open('/tmp/es-sts3.json') as f:\n    sts = json.load(f)\n\nspec = sts['spec']['template']['spec']\n\n# Remove keystore-vol from volumes, keep all others\nspec['volumes'] = [\n    v for v in spec.get('volumes', [])\n    if v['name'] != 'keystore-vol'\n]\n\n# Add es-secure-settings-vol (secret as volume files)\nspec['volumes'].append({\n    \"name\": \"es-secure-settings-vol\",\n    \"secret\": {\n        \"secretName\": \"es-secure-settings\"\n    }\n})\n\n# Remove setup-keystore from initContainers\nspec['initContainers'] = [\n    ic for ic in spec.get('initContainers', [])\n    if ic['name'] != 'setup-keystore'\n]\n\n# Fix main container\nfor c in spec['containers']:\n    if c['name'] == 'elasticsearch':\n        # Remove command/args override from previous attempt\n        c.pop('command', None)\n        c.pop('args', None)\n        \n        # Remove any keystore-vol or es-secure-settings-vol mounts\n        new_mounts = [\n            m for m in c.get('volumeMounts', [])\n            if m['name'] not in ('keystore-vol', 'es-secure-settings-vol')\n        ]\n        # Mount the secret volume so keystore hook can read credentials\n        new_mounts.append({\n            \"name\": \"es-secure-settings-vol\",\n            \"mountPath\": \"/run/secrets/es-secure\",\n            \"readOnly\": True\n        })\n        c['volumeMounts'] = new_mounts\n        \n        # Add postStart lifecycle hook that adds creds to keystore and reloads\n        c['lifecycle'] = {\n            \"postStart\": {\n                \"exec\": {\n                    \"command\": [\"/bin/bash\", \"-c\",\n                        \"elasticsearch-keystore add --stdin --force s3.client.default.access_key \"\n                        \"< /run/secrets/es-secure/s3.client.default.access_key && \"\n                        \"elasticsearch-keystore add --stdin --force s3.client.default.secret_key \"\n                        \"< /run/secrets/es-secure/s3.client.default.secret_key && \"\n                        \"for i in $(seq 1 30); do \"\n                        \"curl -sf -k -u elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD} \"\n                        \"-X POST https://localhost:9200/_nodes/reload_secure_settings \"\n                        \"-H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{}' && break; \"\n                        \"sleep 10; done\"\n                    ]\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        \n        print(\"container spec ready\")\n        print(\"volumeMounts:\", json.dumps(c['volumeMounts'], indent=2))\n        print(\"lifecycle:\", json.dumps(c['lifecycle'], indent=2))\n        break\n\nprint(\"\\nvolumes:\", json.dumps([v['name'] for v in spec['volumes']], indent=2))\nprint(\"initContainers:\", [ic['name'] for ic in spec.get('initContainers', [])])\n\nwith open('/tmp/es-sts3-clean.json', 'w') as f:\n    json.dump(sts, f, indent=2)\nprint(\"Saved clean JSON\")\nPYEOF","description":"Build clean StatefulSet spec with secret volume and postStart lifecycle hook"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":430,"cache_read_input_tokens":69087,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":430},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"823df5a8-cb94-4994-9da9-a4bc1dae2c2d","uuid":"d58459c6-0b86-4719-9867-180e5915305c","request_id":"req_011Ccf4gdevuoTSmrsiHBkh9"}
