{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MVTRzsAEzqapfopabXkcXG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Exit code 143 means the process was killed by SIGTERM (143 = 128 + 15). This often means the hook took too long and was killed. The postStart hook has a timeout.\n\nActually, postStart hooks don't have a configurable timeout, but they are subject to the container's termination grace period. However, 143 (SIGTERM) suggests the hook was terminated.\n\nLooking at the sequence:\n- postStart hook runs immediately when the container starts\n- The hook tries to:\n  1. Add keystore credentials (fast, should work)\n  2. Loop 30 times trying to call reload_secure_settings (each retry has 10s sleep)\n  \nIf Elasticsearch hasn't started yet, the curl call fails 30 times, which takes 300 seconds total. But the default pod termination grace period is only 30 seconds, so the hook gets killed before it finishes. The SIGTERM signal indicates the container was terminated by Kubernetes, not that the hook itself failed.\n\nThe real problem is that the postStart hook is blocking the container from becoming ready. If it takes too long or fails, Kubernetes kills the container. I should simplify the hook to just add the keystore entries without the reload loop, since that's what's causing the timeout. The hook command itself is the issue—it's trying to add S3 credentials to the keystore and then reload secure settings, but if Elasticsearch isn't ready yet, the curl loop exhausts all 30 retries and fails. The postStart hook doesn't have an explicit timeout by default, but it can still fail if ES never becomes available in time, which would cause Kubernetes to kill the container and restart it. As Ready until the postStart hook completes AND the readiness probe passes. So if the hook hangs for 5 minutes, the pod won't be ready for 5 minutes, but it shouldn't fail unless the hook itself exits with non-zero. The hook failing with a non-zero exit code is what triggers the container restart. Now I need to check why the hook command is failing—specifically, I'm wondering if the secret key names in the file path are correct.\n\nThe `es-secure-settings` secret contains `s3.client.default.access_key` and `s3.client.default.secret_key`, which when mounted as a volume become files at `/run/secrets/es-secure/s3.client.default.access_key` and `/run/secrets/es-secure/s3.client.default.secret_key`. The postStart hook uses bash with stdin redirection, which should work fine. The real question is whether `elasticsearch-keystore` is available in the PATH when the hook runs—the hook inherits the container's environment, so it should be there if Elasticsearch is properly installed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":949,"cache_read_input_tokens":81241,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":949},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"823df5a8-cb94-4994-9da9-a4bc1dae2c2d","uuid":"d92403f6-f083-41cc-bb3c-33e34c752179","request_id":"req_011Ccf51DYP4U2bb6izzRCXp"}
